### Interfaces in Kotlin

Interfaces define contracts that classes can implement. Kotlin interfaces can contain abstract methods, concrete methods, and abstract properties.

---

### Declaring an Interface

```kotlin
interface Drivable {
    fun start()  // Abstract method
    fun stop()   // Abstract method
}

class Car : Drivable {
    override fun start() = println("Car starting")
    override fun stop() = println("Car stopping")
}
```

---

### Interface with Default Implementation

```kotlin
interface Logger {
    fun log(message: String)

    fun logInfo(message: String) {  // Default implementation
        log("[INFO] $message")
    }

    fun logError(message: String) {  // Default implementation
        log("[ERROR] $message")
    }
}

class ConsoleLogger : Logger {
    override fun log(message: String) = println(message)
}
```

---

### Interface Properties

Interface properties are abstract by default. They cannot store state.

```kotlin
interface Identifiable {
    val id: String  // Abstract property
    val displayName: String  // Can have getter but no backing field
        get() = "ID: $id"
}

class User(override val id: String) : Identifiable
```

---

### Multiple Interface Implementation

Kotlin supports implementing multiple interfaces.

```kotlin
interface Flyable {
    fun fly() = println("Flying")
}

interface Swimmable {
    fun swim() = println("Swimming")
}

class Duck : Flyable, Swimmable
```

---

### Resolving Conflicting Default Implementations

```kotlin
interface A {
    fun action() = println("Action from A")
}

interface B {
    fun action() = println("Action from B")
}

class C : A, B {
    override fun action() {
        super<A>.action()
        super<B>.action()
    }
}
```

---

### Interface Inheritance

Interfaces can extend other interfaces.

```kotlin
interface Readable {
    fun read(): String
}

interface Writable : Readable {
    fun write(data: String)
}

class FileHandler : Writable {
    override fun read() = "data"
    override fun write(data: String) = println("Writing $data")
}
```

> **Key Point:** Prefer interfaces over abstract classes when you need to define behavior without state. Kotlin's interfaces are more powerful than Java 8 interfaces with support for properties and complex default implementations.

codeExample:
interface Drawable {
    fun draw(): String
    fun description() = "A drawable object"
}

interface Resizable {
    fun resize(factor: Double)
}

class Circle(val radius: Double) : Drawable, Resizable {
    override fun draw() = "Drawing circle with radius $radius"
    override fun resize(factor: Double) {
        // resize logic
    }
    override fun description() = "A circle of radius $radius"
}

fun main() {
    val circle = Circle(5.0)
    println(circle.draw())
    println(circle.description())
}
